[1] Brazil national
Date: Wed 14 Mar 2018
Source: Brazil Ministry of Health [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://portalms.saude.gov.br/noticias/agencia-saude/42788-febre-amarela-ministerio-da-saude-atualiza-casos-no-pais-2


Brazil confirmed 920 [yellow fever] cases and 300 deaths in the period [1 Jul 2017 to 13 Mar 2018]. During the same period last year, there were 610 confirmed cases and 196 deaths.

The Ministry of Health updated the information on [Wed 14 Mar 2018] provided by the state secretariats of health concerning the yellow fever situation in the country. During the monitoring period [1 Jul 2017 to 13 Mar 2018] there were 920 confirmed cases of yellow fever in the country with 300 deaths. In total, during this period 3483 suspected cases were reported, of which 1794 were discarded and 769 remain under investigation.

Last year from July 2016 to [13 Mar 2017], there were 610 confirmed cases and 196 confirmed deaths. These reports of yellow fever cases show a pattern of disease seasonality, occurring mainly in summer, with the period of analysis considered to be [1 Jul-30 Jun] of each year.

Although the number of cases of the current monitoring period have been higher than during the previous season, yellow fever today circulates in metropolitan regions of the country that have the greatest contingent of the population, hitting 32.5 million, including people who live in areas that never had recommendations for [yellow fever] vaccination. In the past season, for example, the outbreak hit a population [at risk] of 8.9 million people.

This explains why the incidence of the disease in this period is lower than in the past period. The incidence of the disease in the monitoring period until [13 Mar 2018] is 2.4 cases for 100 000 inhabitants. In the past season (2016/2017), the incidence was 6.8/100 000 inhabitants, in the same period [but with a smaller population at risk].

Preliminary data sent by the health departments of the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro and São Paulo to the Ministry of Health indicate that the 3 states, before starting the vaccination campaign, had vaccinated about 11.3 million people. During the campaign, up to [13 Mar 2018], 17.8 million people were immunized, which corresponds to 78.6 per cent of the target population. A total of 8.8 million people were vaccinated in São Paulo (94.9 per cent), 6.9 million in Rio de Janeiro (68.5 per cent) and 1.8 million in Bahia (54.3 per cent).

