communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although the yellow fever (YF) outbreak was declared over last year (2017), cases continue to increase, albeit slowly. The above report provides a good update on the current YF situation in Brazil. There is no indication that the outbreak has ended. Although there have been no reports of cases from the urban, _Aedes aegypti_, cycle of transmission the risk remains that spill-over from the sylvan (forest) cycle could occur. _Aedes aegypti_ vector mosquitoes are present in the area and responsible for the transmission of dengue, Zika and chikungunya viruses. It is important to note from the case numbers above that cases of YF in humans and monkeys are occurring in areas outside of the 3 states where the outbreak is occurring. There is risk of new human cases and outbreaks in other areas, so that surveillance in a broad area of Brazil is important.

Maps of Brazil can be accessed at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5696497,6. - Mod.TY]

